This manuscript is included here because it contains the two alphabetical poems printed on p. 55 ff. and p. 60 ff. of the present volume, and also the paragraph, ‘Dicit galienus,’ &o on p. 32. These pieces form an insignificant part of its con- tents; for, although something is lost at the end, the volume still contains about 450 leaves.

There is nothing to shew where it was written3 but it was at St Augustine’s, Canterbury, at least as early as the thir- teenth century. The handwriting, which is what the con- tinental authorities call ‘ insular,' shews that it was copied by an Englishman: some of the contents, which relate to the Emperor Henry III (1039—1055) give us a date before which it cannot have been written, while the writing itself prevents us from placing it much later.
